ce:section.ce:para:
Photo-induced charge transfer (PICT) processes are ubiquitous in nature, and mimicking these reactions has been a theme of intense research in nanoscience for their applications in catalysis, energy, imaging, and opto-electronics [1–3]. Compared to the bulk materials, the interfacial charge transfer at the nanometer-sized low-dimensional materials has been widely investigated for tuning their quantum confinement induced optical and electronic properties. The PICT kinetics between the donor (D) and acceptor (A) in bulk materials have been accurately predicted by Marcus non-adiabatic electron transfer (ET) theory [4]. However, due to the complexity of the interface of these nanoscale materials, a comprehensive theoretical approach in various hybrid D-A systems is yet to emerge. While factors like D-A distance, electronic coupling, free energy, solvent reorganization energy, etc., are important for determining the rate of ET (k

                        ET

                     ) in the Marcus theory. Additional parameters like confinement effects, ionic properties of the interface, trap states, surface functionalization, bandgap, carrier density, etc., have to be also accounted for nanomaterials [5,6]. With the advances in molecular electronics and photonics, the role of intervening bridge in charge migration from D to A has also been explored by Ratner et al. [7]. They developed a unified description for the ET in a D-bridge-A system to the conductance of the same bridge in the metal-molecule-metal junction. Experimental techniques like time-resolved photoluminescence, transient absorptions, etc., have been useful for the precise determination of ET rates. In contrast, electro-migration break junctions, current sensing atomic force microscopy, scanning tunneling microscopes, etc., are used for electronic transport measurements across the metal-molecule-metal junctions [8].

To obtain further insight into the unabridged mechanism, we have observed the Stern-Volmer (S–V) plot (Fig. 5
                     ) from lifetime values given by Equation (3). The values of quenching constants (KSV) are calculated from the slopes obtained from S–V plots for both UCDs and ACDs in the H2O–EtOH mixture and CTAB are tabulated in the inset of Fig. 5. As shown here, the quenching of UCDs is much faster in CTAB with KSV value of 423 M−1 than in the H2O–EtOH mixture with KSV value of 8 M−1. While ACDs in H2O–EtOH mixture have less KSV value than UCDs in CTAB given as 190 M−1, but this value is less in CTAB medium than in H2O–EtOH mixture (45 M−1). These values of KSV for these CDs are comparable to the reported values by Sun et al. [48]. As shown in the inset of Fig. 5, the maximum efficiency is evaluated for UCDs in CTAB (42%) than in the H2O–EtOH mixture (3%) by using Equation (4). However, if we compare for ACDs, the efficiency is more (15%) in the H2O–EtOH mixture than CTAB (2%). These results reveal that the excited state quenching rate in CTAB is higher for UCDs compared to ACDs. The mechanism behind this can be well-explained by Scheme 2
                     .

To explicitly assign a charge transport mechanism for the unforeseen result, we have plotted ln (I/V2) ∼ 1/V (Equation (7)) from the same I–V curve shown in Fig. 7
                     . The stimulating behavior observed here is an inflection point. This point converges the two regimes, such as direct and F–N tunneling, which indicates the conversion of the rectangular barrier to triangular one at the junction [78,87]. The bias at the inflection point (Vtrans) gives rise to two distinct voltage regimes, the transport in the low bias region can be fitted by the exponential growth equation while at higher bias develops linear one [88]. Hence, the current becomes saturated before attaining the large barrier height, leads to a direct tunneling current. Moreover, the thoughtful analysis shows that the transition voltage of UCDs varies from H2O–EtOH mixture to CTAB from 0.57 to 0.43 V, while there is no change (0.53 V) in this value in ACDs (Table 2
                     ). This is also consistent with the resistance values, which enhances the curiosity to get insight into the realism of the system. Moreover, the above spectroscopic analysis clarifies that ET is not feasible in the CTAB medium due to electrostatic repulsion between ACDs and CTAB without changing its fluorescence lifetime. This gives a direct information about the interaction of the environmental condition perturbing the transition voltage of CDs at their interfaces, as the electrostatic interaction is possible between the surface of CD to the surrounding medium. Conversely, no interaction happens in ACDs to CTAB due to repulsion by the same charge group. Hence, the cationic surface charge of CTAB cannot be able to modulate the emission moieties of ACDs.
